tance.\\n\\nComparing against the previous state, the cron jobs show progress—the first one's been active for about 11 minutes now, and the agent status cron is running with a recent update. The rest of the sessions remain unchanged, so the overall picture is stable. The cron:e7885813 is showing as running in the current state with an updatedAt timestamp of 1776170681044, which is more recent than the 12:34 timestamp from the heartbeat state—so that's an update rather than a zombie session. The cron:b653a6c0 also appears to be running based on the current session list.\\n\\nLooking at the updatedAt values, cron:b653a6c0 is actually more recent (1776167853466) compared to what the heartbeat state shows (lastSeen at 11:53), suggesting it's still active. The cron:e7885813 is confirmed as running since it's in the current sessions list, and since it wasn't in the previous state, this indicates it has newly started or is continuing from before. Looking at the heartbeat state more carefully, the `updatedAt` timestamp for cron:e7885813 shows 1776170681044, but that doesn't align with the `lastSeen` value of 12:34. Since the heartbeat check runs every 5 minutes, it's possible the session started after the previous heartbeat was recorded, or there's a mismatch in how these timestamps are being compared. Looking at the session details, cron:e7885813 was actually started at 1776168854226, which is around 12:34 UTC, but the previous heartbeat state shows a different `updatedAt` value. The discrepancy is likely because this cron session either wasn't captured in the earlier sessions_list response or wasn't listed at all in the 12:46 check. I'm realizing the confusion—when I said \\\"running\\\" in the last heartbeat, I meant that was the status at that time, but now the updatedAt timestamp is 1776170681044, which is later, so the session has definitely been updated since then. I need to reconsider what the cron:e7885813 status actually was in the previous heartbeat state. I'm wondering if this is a new session that just started, which would be a real change, but it's hard to say for certain without more context. The session ID is the same between both checks, so it's the same persistent cron session, but the updatedAt timestamp has changed from 1776168854226 to 1776170681044—that's roughly a 30-minute gap in activity. Looking at the timestamp from the cron:e7885813 session, it shows 1776170681044, which converts to 2026-04-14T12:44:41 UTC—right around when the previous heartbeat ran. So it seems like this cron session was indeed running at 12:44-12:46 but might not have shown up in the sessions list snapshot at that exact moment.\\n\\nNow comparing the current state to the heartbeat: most sessions are stable, but cron:e7885813 has updated with a new timestamp, which signals it's still active. That's the only real change to report. Let me finish checking the remaining sessions. Looking at the rest of the session statuses, most are unchanged from the previous cycle. The cron:e7885813 session is still running but hasn't generated a new report since 12:34 UTC, which is notable since it's been about 17 minutes without activity. The stale zombie session b653a6c0 remains dormant as well.\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out if the heartbeat file is capturing the actual last update time or if it's just reflecting when it was first detected. The timestamps don't quite line up with the session metadata—b653a6c0 shows an updatedAt value of around 12:37 UTC, but the heartbeat says it was last seen at 11:53, which seems off by about 44 minutes.\\n\\nLet me recalculate more carefully. Converting those milliseconds to seconds and working through the date math, the updatedAt timestamp for cron:e7885813 actually corresponds to 2026-04-14T12:44:41 UTC, not 12:34. So the heartbeat timestamp of 1776170681044 is correct, and that 30-minute gap between the last activity and now makes sense.\\n\\nFor cron:b653a6c0, the updatedAt value converts to 2026-04-14T11:37:33 UTC, which is 44 minutes before the stated lastSeen time. These discrepancies suggest the heartbeat state was recorded before the sessions were fully indexed, so I should rely on the current sessions_list as the authoritative source. The key finding is that both cron:e7885813 and cron:b653a6c0 are still running, with no new sessions created since the last heartbeat. Looking at the session list, I can confirm the two cron jobs are still active—cron:e7885813 was updated at 12:44 and cron:b653a6c0 at 11:37—and there's one new change where the Agent Status cron has a more recent update timestamp, though that's just within the existing session. Everything else checks out as stable, so the system is operating normally.\\n\\nWait, I need to reconsider the timing here. The cron session that ran at 12:44 appears to have delivered its output, but I'm not seeing a new Agent Status report come through since 12:34. That's 17 minutes of silence when these reports typically go out every 15 minutes. This could be a timing coincidence since the previous heartbeat was at 12:46 and we're now at 12:51—right in the middle of that window—but it might also signal that the cron isn't firing as expected or the reports aren't reaching the group.\\n\\nLooking at the pipeline health, nothing's actually changed from the last heartbeat. The Agent Status cron is still running, the zombie session is still there, and all the infrastructure checks are passing. I should stay silent and not send another report. Let me double-check the current session timestamps one more time to make sure I'm not missing anything. Comparing the session states against the last heartbeat, everything's holding steady—no new failures, no fresh blockers, no completed tasks to report. The system remains healthy, so I'm going to stay silent and let the previous report stand.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Comparing current state against `heartbeat-state.json` (last