ill running but hasn't been seen since 12:44, and cron:b653a6c0 is another zombie session with an updatedAt of 11:37:33 UTC. There's also a subagent session for the full API test that failed early this morning and hasn't changed.\n\nLooking at the remaining subagents, most of the failed ones are from the same timeframe, with a couple from late morning. The cron:53c5832a session from the daily briefing is still present in the session list with no status field, while the earlier cron:ac986a8d is now showing as done.\n\nComparing this against the heartbeat state from 12:46 UTC, the 5p QLHV cron is still running with an updated timestamp, the 5p DTLX cron is also still active, and the QLHV group session remains unchanged.\n\nThe DTLX group session, Lead direct, and main heartbeat session all show as done with no changes. For the agent status cron, the timestamp shows 12:44 UTC, which is 7 minutes before the 12:51 current time—so it's stale. The zombie session from 11:53 is still present and hasn't been cleared.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, everything from the last heartbeat state is still there with no new sessions spawned, no unexpected deaths, and no new failures introduced. The cron sessions are updating normally, and the stale agent status cron is just a known pre-existing condition. Since there haven't been any actual changes, I'm doing a silent exit. I'm recalculating the uptime for the Agent Status cron—it's been running about 19 minutes since 12:34 UTC. But looking back at the heartbeat history, the 12:44 report was the last one delivered, and the 12:51 session shows no new report generated, which suggests either the cron stopped firing or the reports stopped being sent to Telegram around that time. Looking at the timestamps, the cron:e7885813 was definitely running at 12:44, but I need to figure out if it's still active now at 12:51 or if it's gone stale. The 12:34 `lastSeen` in the heartbeat state might just be an older value that wasn't updated in the 12:46 snapshot, so I'm checking the current `updatedAt` to determine the actual status. So the cron session was actively running during that earlier heartbeat at 12:44 UTC, which means the `lastSeen` value of 12:34 was probably just outdated—it should have been 12:44 based on when the session was actually last updated. This suggests the heartbeat tracking wasn't perfectly synchronized with the actual session activity.\n\nNow at 12:51 UTC, the cron:e7885813 session has an `updatedAt` timestamp of 12:44:41, which is about 6 minutes old. That's within the 15-minute cron interval, so this session appears to be still alive and responsive rather than stale. The fact that there's no recent message from this session in the Telegram direct history is interesting—either it hasn't fired its next cycle yet, or the messages aren't showing up in the conversation. So the real issue is that cron:e7885813 hasn't generated a new report since 12:44 UTC—that's 17 minutes ago when these crons should fire every 15 minutes. Looking back at the heartbeat state, the session was active at 12:34 and 12:44, but there's a gap in what I can see from the Telegram history itself, which makes it harder to pinpoint exactly when it stopped reporting. The cron:e7885813 session shows activity at 12:44 based on the updatedAt timestamp, and there's a 12:51 report dispatched through the QLHV cron session, so I'll mark it as stable. The overall state hasn't changed—nothing new has spawned or failed, the pipeline is healthy, and the system is stable, so I'm doing a silent exit."},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current `sessions_list` (36 sessions) against `heartbeat-state.json` (last check: 12:46 UTC):\n\n**Sessions vs. last state:**\n| Session | Last (12:46) | Current (12:51) | Δ |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `cron:ed2d0b5d` (5p QLHV) | running | running ✅ | normal tick |\n| `cron:6f3323ef` (5p DTLX) | running | running ✅ | normal tick |\n| `telegram:group:-5163901258` | running | running ✅ | stable |\n| `telegr