Agent Status cron typically fires every 15 minutes, so if the last one was at 12:44, the next would be due at 12:59. Since the sessions list still shows it as running, it hasn't died, but I can't confirm whether it actually fired at 12:44 because I don't have access to those logs. The session could be in the middle of executing the next check right now, or it could be stuck waiting for the next cycle.\n\nLooking at the other cron sessions, the two 5p progress monitors are definitely running—cron:ed2d0b5d has been going for about 2 hours 54 minutes and cron:6f3323ef for roughly 3 hours 44 minutes. The cron:ac986a8d session appears to be an old Telegram delivery job that's been stuck since around 07:04 UTC, possibly due to repeated execution failures, so that's a zombie that won't clear on its own.\n\nNow I need to figure out whether cron:e7885813 (the agent status checker) is actually still healthy or if it's also gone stale like the others.\n\nLooking at the session data, cron:e7885813 has updatedAt 1776170681044 which converts to 12:44:41 UTC, putting it at about 9 minutes old—definitely not fresh. The previous heartbeat reported it at 12:44 with an \"Agent Status\" label, and there's a 12:44 status report showing 5 active sessions, but I need to reconcile why the updatedAt timestamp seems off from the label. I'm seeing the same report from 12:44:45 UTC sent twice within seconds of each other, which looks like a delivery attempt rather than two separate reports. The timestamps in the provenance field and the updatedAt time for that cron session align at around 12:44-12:45 UTC, suggesting this cron did fire at least once, though the duplicates suggest there might have been a retry mechanism at play.\n\nNow I'm tracking the pattern of when these reports actually appear in the Telegram session. The reports show up at 12:44, 12:46, and 12:48 UTC, but there's a gap at 12:49 where the expected report at 12:49:41 never shows up. The cron:e7885813 session itself is still running in the sessions list with activity around 12:44, but I'm wondering if it's stuck waiting for a tool call or something else is preventing it from firing again.\n\nLooking at the 5p cron sessions to understand the pattern—they're running and sending reports to the Telegram group at regular intervals, and the 5p QLHV cron appears to be delivering to the same group ID as the Agent Status reports. So the cron is definitely active, but the Agent Status report seems to have stalled between 12:48 and now.\n\nGiven that there are 3 active sessions including this one, I should send a report, though I'll need to mark cron:e7885813 as stale or degraded since it's not delivering. Let me calculate the exact runtimes from the start times to get precise durations. I'm seeing that the Agent Status cron session is stale at 12 minutes old, while the Telegram delivery cron is severely outdated at 5+ hours. So I've identified three active cron sessions total—the two 5p Progress Report monitors and the Agent Status cron—but the Agent Status cron itself is stuck and not producing any output.\n\nLooking back at the previous report from 12:44, it flagged the Agent Status cron as stale, which matches what I'm seeing now, so this is a known issue that's persisting. The cron session itself is still registered but hasn't fired since that last report.\n\nI should compose a brief status update with all three active sessions and send it through.","thinkingSignature":"f6abb9ba0d863ebade7a0158ad730552cd6751b6bf7ce8824097ea3a7c356b10"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wz2xr0d51hq8_1","name":"sessions_send","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134","message":"🌐 Orbis — Agent Status | 12:54 UTC 14 Apr\n\nActive sessions: 3\n• cron:ed2d0b5d (5p QLHV): running — 5-min progress monitoring (QLHV ecosystem) — ~2h 54m\n• cron:6f3323ef (5p DTLX): running — 5-min progress monitoring (DTLX ecosystem) — ~3h 44m\n• cron:e7885813 (Agent Status): running — status 