{"type":"message","id":"98ed3248","parentId":"4f29d627","timestamp":"2026-04-14T12:56:33.824Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The sessions_send timed out. The Telegram session is done. Let me try again with a simpler message or just reply HEARTBEAT_OK.\n\nActually, looking at the previous history - the Lead Telegram session was \"done\" with status=done, endedAt 1776162158012. That means it ended around 12:15 UTC. The session is closed. So sending to it would time out.\n\nLet me send to the current active telegram:direct session. But looking at sessions_list, there's only one direct:agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134 which is done.\n\nHmm, maybe I should send to the webchat session or just reply with HEARTBEAT_OK.\n \nThe cron:e7885813 was sending reports directly to the Telegram session earlier, and looking at the session timestamps, it does show \"done\" status, but the cron itself is still registered and presumably still trying to send. The previous heartbeat was still polling this session before it completed, so there's a disconnect between what the session history shows and what's actually still running. I'm realizing the session_send timeout might be because the target session has already ended—the \"done\" status with an endedAt timestamp of 1776162158012 (around 12:15 UTC) suggests it's no longer active, even though the cron job itself is still registered and trying to deliver messages to it. The real issue is that the cron job keeps attempting to send reports to an ended session, which causes delivery failures and timeouts. I should probably stop the cron job, but I can't do that directly—I need to notify the operator about this stuck delivery loop. Let me try sending to the webchat session instead, though that's already done too.\n\nLooking at the 5p cron history, those reports did reach the Telegram group at 11:53 and 12:04, so the delivery mechanism is working for active sessions. The problem is 